content.text: How TO - Remove a Property from an Object
Learn how to remove a property from a JavaScript object.
content.html: Learn how to remove a property from a JavaScript object.

content.text: The delete operator deletes a property from an object:
content.html: The delete operator deletes a property from an object:

syntaxHighlighting.text:
// Before deletion: person.age = 50, after deletion, person.age = 
  undefined

syntax_highlighting.text:
// Before deletion: person.age = 50, after deletion, person.age = 
  undefined

content.code_html:
var person = {
  firstName: "John",
  lastName: "Doe",
  age: 50,
  eyeColor: "blue"
};

delete person.age;  // or delete person["age"];

// Before deletion: person.age = 50, after deletion, person.age = undefined

syntax_highlighting_data.text:
// Before deletion: person.age = 50, after deletion, person.age = 
  undefined

content.text: The delete operator deletes both the value of the property and the property itself.
content.html: The delete operator deletes both the value of the property and the property itself.

content.text: After deletion, the property cannot be used before it is added back again.
content.html: After deletion, the property cannot be used before it is added back again.

content.text: The delete operator is designed to be used on object properties. It has no effect on variables or functions.
content.html: The delete operator is designed to be used on object properties. It has no effect on variables or functions.

content.text: Note: The delete operator should not be used on predefined JavaScript object properties. It can crash your application.
content.html: Note: The delete operator should not be used on predefined JavaScript object properties. It can crash your application.
